00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:54.660
So, Hindemith was born in Hanau,

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:59.090
Germany near Frankfurt,
on November 16, 1898.

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:02.980
He died also, in Frankfurt in 1963.

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.710
He was the oldest of three
siblings; learned the violin first,

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:07.560 position:56%
then he started studying composition

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:09.980
at the Hoch's Konservatorium
[phonetic] in Frankfurt.

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.330
One of his teachers
was Arnold Mendelssohn,

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:14.660
who was the great nephew of Felix.

00:04:14.660 --> 00:04:17.680
He was also the same
teacher of Adorno,

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:19.680
which I find very interesting.

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:24.100
Hindemith didn't stick with the
violin, and he later switched

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:28.210
over to viola, and became
a composer of course,

00:04:28.210 --> 00:04:32.210 position:56%
he was a significant music theorist,
an educator, and a conductor.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:35.930
He also published several
theoretical treatises

00:04:35.930 --> 00:04:39.820
and some pedagogical texts as well.

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:43.600
So, getting into the
World War One time frame,

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.620
that was a very brief overview of
his biography, go read something,

00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:48.610
you don't want to hear me
ramble about that all day.

00:04:48.610 --> 00:04:50.010
So, World War One.

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:57.130
Hindemith's father; Robert Rudolf
Emil Hindemith, was born in 1870 --

00:04:57.130 --> 00:05:01.640 position:56%
was one of the driving forces behind
Hindemith becoming a musician.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:05.440
He was a musician, he forced
his children to pretty much get

00:05:05.440 --> 00:05:07.420
in the track to become musicians.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:09.680
He was very active in getting
Hindemith opportunities

00:05:09.680 --> 00:05:12.690
with teachers, putting him into
conservatories with scholarships,

00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:15.440
and even opening the door for jobs.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:20.610
Just about the time of 1914,
the relationship soured,

00:05:20.610 --> 00:05:24.500
I haven't gotten in enough
depth in the German text,

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:26.660
to see exactly why that was.

00:05:26.660 --> 00:05:30.250
It seems like Hindemith, probably
didn't talk too much about it.

00:05:30.250 --> 00:05:32.680
But, right about the time
that it became strange,

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:36.370
Hindemith's father went to fight
in World War One, since 1914,

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:40.740
and he was killed within
that first year of conflict.

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:44.980
So, that left Hindemith's
mother without the income

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:48.140
for the household, and
Hindemith had to quickly adapt

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:51.110
to become the principal
bread winner for the family.

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:54.340
He joined the Frankfurt opera
orchestra in 1914, he was promoted

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:57.280
to Deputy Leader, Deputy
Concert Master later that year,

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:01.280
and he became the Concert
Master in 1917.

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:04.820
Hindemith was very evolved
in chamber music playing,

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:07.380
notably joining the
Rebner String Quartet,

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:11.500
from 1915 as the second violinist,
and later in 1923, was the switch

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:15.450
to viola that we mentioned earlier.

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:18.360
So, Hindemith was busy working in
Frankfurt, he was a freelancer,

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:21.030
he also had these permanent gigs,
where he was relatively well paid,

00:06:21.030 --> 00:06:22.620
compared to a lot of other people.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:28.870
And he kind of got away with not
having been conscripted initially,

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:30.600
because there was a draft.

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:36.110
One of the biographers goes
in depth into something

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:40.790
that really puts the effect of
World War One into perspective; so,

00:06:40.790 --> 00:06:44.320
Hindemith, on the outside of
the war, had a lot of German,

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:47.140
nationalist kind of concepts.

00:06:47.140 --> 00:06:51.450
Not super nationalist, not super
imperialist like other folks.

00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:54.050
But, you can see his
attitude towards the war,

00:06:54.050 --> 00:06:56.830
and towards his own
government positions evolved

00:06:56.830 --> 00:06:58.430
over the course of the war.

00:06:58.430 --> 00:07:02.970
So, on September 23rd,
1914; Hindemith said, quote,

00:07:02.970 --> 00:07:05.330
"Everyone is glad that the
French are getting a good blow,

00:07:05.330 --> 00:07:08.020
and if one goes into town
towards noon, or in the evening;

00:07:08.020 --> 00:07:11.740
there's a crowd such as one
seldom notices in peaceful times,

00:07:11.740 --> 00:07:14.030
in the entire empire
there's the great optimism

00:07:14.030 --> 00:07:16.850
that Germany will win, and when
you see all the happy soldiers

00:07:16.850 --> 00:07:18.630
that are still here,
and the enthusiasm,

00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:20.890
you know this cannot be otherwise.

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:23.440
Everyone is delighted to go
into the field, and when you see

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:26.340
that everyone is happy to grab
a weapon, and no one wants

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:28.700
to stay behind, even
enemies will have to admit

00:07:28.700 --> 00:07:32.290
that the German people are fighting
for a just cause, and have not,

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:35.750
as the French, Russian and
English live factories,

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:39.320
wished to propagate gun to
war, just for rowdiness.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.790
Don't think that what I'm
writing is an exaggeration.

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:44.290
The numbers are set too low,
the people are set in a state

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:48.830
of enormous enthusiasm", obviously,
that didn't last for most people,

00:07:48.830 --> 00:07:51.860
and the central powers
there just given the scale

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:53.450
of destruction and death.

00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:57.290
Hindemith was initially
called up for service in 1915,

00:07:57.290 --> 00:08:01.770
but he was rejected and he wrote of
this to some friends, "They haven't

00:08:01.770 --> 00:08:04.730
yet taken me up into the ranks
of the defenders of our country,

00:08:04.730 --> 00:08:06.110
and I'm not angry about it.

00:08:06.110 --> 00:08:08.010
I was examined twice,
but was rejected due

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:10.720
to general physical
weakness and heart defects.

00:08:10.720 --> 00:08:12.660
There will probably be more
examinations coming up,

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:15.420
and I have no hope of
coming back again."

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:18.450
So, that's within a year,
he's from September 14,

00:08:18.450 --> 00:08:21.830
to September 15 his attitude
just switched, and maybe,

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:23.700
there was out of context going
on, but that's what we have

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:26.590 position:56%
in some correspondence to go off of.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:30.980
So, he was eventually
conscripted, and in August of 1917,

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:33.440
and throughout these first
few years of the war,

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:35.960
he was just in Frankfurt
working, basically.

00:08:35.960 --> 00:08:39.710
And his training period
started on August 1917,

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:44.990
and then in January 1918, he was
sent close to the front in Alsace,

00:08:44.990 --> 00:08:49.150
with a regime, and eventually on
to Flanders, on the summer of 1918.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:53.240
One of the things that shows
Hindemith's entrepreneurial skill,

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:57.730
or persuasive skills, is
that he lobbied the director

00:08:57.730 --> 00:09:03.020
of the Frankfurt Opera Theater, to
keep him on salary in his position,

00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:05.370
while he was off fighting.

00:09:05.370 --> 00:09:07.380
So, nowadays if you're in
the military and you work

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:08.970 position:56%
for the government, you have 15 days

00:09:08.970 --> 00:09:11.460
of military leave a year,
which is very generous.

00:09:11.460 --> 00:09:15.600
So, basically getting paid
leave time, be in service,

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.330
but it expires at a certain point.

00:09:17.330 --> 00:09:20.150
Hindemith actually
negotiated to get 70%

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:23.580
of his salary paid while
he was away and not working

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:26.130
for the Opera Orchestra,
which is pretty cool.

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:31.300
And his boss there, was generous
and didn't seem to put up much

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:33.040
of a fight about that,
given that the --

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:38.310
he very much asked for empathy,
because of his mother situation

00:09:38.310 --> 00:09:40.480
and not having a father anymore.

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:44.420
So, in the war, Hindemith was
assigned to the regimental band,

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:46.890
this is a good place for
professional musicians

00:09:46.890 --> 00:09:49.760
to go during sort of
total war situations,

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:52.610
it's the same in the American
military in World War One,

00:09:52.610 --> 00:09:54.550
World War Two; folks
like Glenn Miller,

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:59.430
serving Elvis during his
little PR service, right?

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:03.700
And Hindemith, because
it was basically a brass

00:10:03.700 --> 00:10:08.500
and percussion sort of -- Drum
and Bugle Corp kind of ensemble,

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:10.760
he played bass drum, there
was not an opportunity

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:13.560
for him to play the violin.

00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:17.420
That is initial entry
to the regimental band.

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:23.040
He kind of seems to have
appreciated that he was

00:10:23.040 --> 00:10:28.900
in a cushy service job basically,
and he wrote to some friends in May

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:33.150
of 1918, quote, "I can hardly
imagine most musicians as soldiers;

00:10:33.150 --> 00:10:35.950
Bach as a staff Sargent,
that would still be OK,

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:39.220 position:56%
but Beethoven practicing rightful
drum, Mozart throwing hand grenades,

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:41.150
or standing guard in
front of a barracks.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:44.520
Shubert as an Air Force Lieutenant,
and Mendelssohn as an NCO

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:50.780
at a vehicle fleet convoy that
is inconceivable", end quote.

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:54.720 position:56%
So, Hindemith did have down time, in
which to compose, and very quickly

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:56.830
after he got tired of
playing bass drum alone,

00:10:56.830 --> 00:11:01.410 position:56%
he joined in a string quartet with
some others in the military service,

00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:03.480
and that became a big
part of his duties,

00:11:03.480 --> 00:11:05.900
was to play string
quartet repertoire

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:11.640
for the commanding officer, who
was a very sort of well read,

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:14.410
learned type of guy who
enjoyed this classical music.

00:11:14.410 --> 00:11:15.810
And that was a really
good opportunity

00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:18.790
for Hindemith to take advantage of.

00:11:18.790 --> 00:11:20.940
So, they were mostly
back from the frontlines,

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:26.030
as a result of his entertainment
role, and ceremonial role,

00:11:26.030 --> 00:11:34.040
and eventually, they did get sent
in to sort of guards situations,

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:37.990
which I'll get into a second,
but one of the evenings or days,

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:39.920
where he was performing
for the commanding officer

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:41.730 position:56%
in the string quartet, they happened

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:44.450
to be performing Debussy's
[phonetic] Quartet,

00:11:44.450 --> 00:11:47.180
and while they were
performing they got word

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:48.550
that Debussy had passed away.

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:53.180
This was in 1918, March 25th
was when he passed away.

00:11:53.180 --> 00:11:59.580
Hindemith is -- one of his most
well-known quotes is the following,

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:01.010
quote, "We did not
play to the end --

00:12:01.010 --> 00:12:03.420
this is referring to that
performance of the Debussy --

00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:06.550
it was as if our playing had been
robbed of the breath of life,

00:12:06.550 --> 00:12:11.670
that we realized for the first
time that music is more than style,

00:12:11.670 --> 00:12:14.810
technique and the expression
of powerful feelings;

00:12:14.810 --> 00:12:16.900
music reached out beyond
political boundaries,

00:12:16.900 --> 00:12:19.410
national hatred and
the horse of war.

00:12:19.410 --> 00:12:21.040
On no other occasion have I seen

00:12:21.040 --> 00:12:24.530
so clearly what direction
music must take".

00:12:24.530 --> 00:12:29.510
So, that definitely shows us,

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:32.260
I think that Hindemith was a
very enlightened individual,

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:35.060
he was thinking about
what he was experiencing,

00:12:35.060 --> 00:12:39.440
and this kind of discourse
on the role of music

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:42.200
in these conflict situations
plays an interesting role

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:43.550
in the rest of his life.

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:45.630
And this is very much the
formative period with this --

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:49.000
because he got into conflicts of
course, with the Nazis later on,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:54.500
in terms of his positions, and
the conservatory, and advocating

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:55.840
for composers who were being pushed

00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:59.800
out for political or
religious reasons.

00:12:59.800 --> 00:13:05.880 position:56%
This is the foundation of Hindemith,
as the sort of noble, intellectual,

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:08.580
standing up for what's
right through his music.

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:11.950
He wasn't a radical with
it, at all, it's more --

00:13:11.950 --> 00:13:15.230
it fits into this concept
of expressionism,

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:20.690 position:56%
where he was using the music to give
a very individualized accounting

00:13:20.690 --> 00:13:24.250
of emotions and personal responses,

00:13:24.250 --> 00:13:27.840
especially through the text based
works, the vocal chamber music,

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:32.250
which we're going to
get into in depth.

00:13:32.250 --> 00:13:36.090
One other joke that he made
about the bass drum in his time

00:13:36.090 --> 00:13:37.950
of service, was, "I was assured

00:13:37.950 --> 00:13:41.680
that this instrument had never been
before treated so rhythmically;

00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:44.260
service is not so hard, I have
a lot of free time and can work

00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:49.010
in what I want", end quote.

00:13:49.010 --> 00:13:54.880
So, later in the war, on
May of 1918, in Flanders,

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:59.950
where he was stationed, he writes
about his experiences of being,

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:01.250
really on the frontlines,

00:14:01.250 --> 00:14:03.380
rather than several
kilometers back before, right?

00:14:03.380 --> 00:14:05.400
If you're playing as
a string quartet,

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:07.080
while people are dying it's not --

00:14:07.080 --> 00:14:08.700
you're probably not
on the frontlines.

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:11.910
So, he writes about being closer
to the combat situation, quote,

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:14.770
"Towards the evening, eight
bombs were thrown near the town,

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:18.160
one hit the ammunition convoy
that [inaudible] 10 minutes away

00:14:18.160 --> 00:14:20.020
from us, a horrible sight.

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:23.740
Blood, bodies full of holes,
brains, a torn off horse's head,

00:14:23.740 --> 00:14:27.780
splintered bones, dreadful; how
mean and indifferent one becomes.

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:30.940
I don't think I could've eaten
or worked in peace before,

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:35.240
since such a sight -- excuse me --
after seeing such a sight, and now,

00:14:35.240 --> 00:14:38.250
one sits at home again;
writing, chatting in a good mood,

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:40.950
not thinking about how soon
the bell could toll for us.

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:45.580 position:56%
It's gradually becoming creepy here,
we're going to withdraw unharmed".

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:49.190
There's a lot of different
emotions going on, right?

00:14:49.190 --> 00:14:52.680
He's going from being at a
pretty protected situation,

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:57.070
to being more towards the combat
experience, seeing what's going on,

00:14:57.070 --> 00:14:59.390
and I think a lot of the sort of --

00:14:59.390 --> 00:15:01.970
the concepts that he is reflecting
on, on that statement in terms

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:05.020
of experiencing and
witnessing visually, the gore

00:15:05.020 --> 00:15:08.630
and the death come through in a
lot of the text that he selected

00:15:08.630 --> 00:15:11.750
for his musical compositions.

00:15:11.750 --> 00:15:15.380
When he heard of the end of
the war, in November 1918,

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:18.090
