00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:35.870
So, that's that sort of cross
currents happening simultaneously.

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:42.240
Some of the concepts
that Hindemith addresses

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:46.570
in the World War One text
settings, come up again and again,

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:50.120
in some of his more famous
works, from later in his career,

00:21:50.120 --> 00:21:53.090
including Mathis der
Maler, which tells the story

00:21:53.090 --> 00:21:56.700
of Matthias Grünewald, the
painter, and the Harmonie der Welt,

00:21:56.700 --> 00:21:58.920
which tells the story about Kepler.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:03.170 position:56%
Both of those operas deal with the
conflict of the individual identity,

00:22:03.170 --> 00:22:06.840 position:56%
and the sort of situation of social
upheaval, regardless of the context.

00:22:06.840 --> 00:22:08.440
So, I think, Hindemith
throughout his career,

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:12.090
even though he didn't spend all of
his time focusing on social issues

00:22:12.090 --> 00:22:16.110
in his music, there's definitely
this thing about him that sticks

00:22:16.110 --> 00:22:20.280 position:56%
to that topic, whether it's specific
to World War One experiences,

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:22.850
whether is revisiting
historical figures,

00:22:22.850 --> 00:22:26.660
and seeing how history
repeats itself unfortunately.

00:22:26.660 --> 00:22:29.460
And the two figures
